    <h1>Static, Readonly, and Const in C#</h1>
    <p>
        In C#, you will often work with values that should not change or should be shared across
        all objects of a class. For this purpose, we use <strong>static</strong>, <strong>readonly</strong>,
        and <strong>const</strong>. While they may look similar at first, they behave differently.
    </p>

    <h2>1. Static</h2>
    <p>
        A <strong>static</strong> member belongs to the <em>class itself</em>, not to any single object.
        This means you can use it without creating an object.
        It is useful when something is common for all objects (like a counter, a utility method, or Pi in math).
    </p>

    <!-- Static Example -->
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">
            Example: Static Member
            <div class="toggle-wrapper">
                <label class="toggle-label">C#</label>
                <label class="switch">
                    <input type="checkbox" id="staticToggle">
                    <span class="slider round"></span>
                </label>
                <label class="toggle-label">C</label>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp static-code">
public class Calculator
{
    public static double Pi = 3.14159;
}

// Usage:
Console.WriteLine(Calculator.Pi); // Output: 3.14159
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="language-c static-code" style="display:none;">
#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

double Pi = 3.14159;

int main() {
    printf("%f\n", Pi); // Output: 3.14159
    return 0;
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>2. Readonly</h2>
    <p>
        A <strong>readonly</strong> field can only be set:
        <ul>
            <li>When declaring the field, OR</li>
            <li>Inside a constructor (when the object is created).</li>
        </ul>
        Once set, its value cannot be changed.
        This is useful when each object should keep its own value that never changes after construction.
    </p>

    <!-- Readonly Example -->
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">
            Example: Readonly Field
            <div class="toggle-wrapper">
                <label class="toggle-label">C#</label>
                <label class="switch">
                    <input type="checkbox" id="readonlyToggle">
                    <span class="slider round"></span>
                </label>
                <label class="toggle-label">C</label>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp readonly-code">
public class Circle
{
    public readonly double Radius;

    public Circle(double radius)
    {
        Radius = radius; // Set once when object is created
    }
}

Circle c = new Circle(5);
// c.Radius = 10; // ❌ Error: Cannot assign to readonly field
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="language-c readonly-code" style="display:none;">
#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

struct Circle {
    double Radius;
};

int main() {
    struct Circle c;
    c.Radius = 5;
    // c.Radius = 10; // You can avoid changing by convention
    printf("%f\n", c.Radius);
    return 0;
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>3. Const</h2>
    <p>
        A <strong>const</strong> field is a constant value that never changes.
        It must be assigned when declared, and the compiler replaces every usage with its value.
        Use <code>const</code> for values that are absolutely fixed (like gravity, days in a week, etc.).
    </p>

    <!-- Const Example -->
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">
            Example: Const Field
            <div class="toggle-wrapper">
                <label class="toggle-label">C#</label>
                <label class="switch">
                    <input type="checkbox" id="constToggle">
                    <span class="slider round"></span>
                </label>
                <label class="toggle-label">C</label>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp const-code">
public class MathConstants
{
    public const double Gravity = 9.81;
}

// Usage:
Console.WriteLine(MathConstants.Gravity); // Output: 9.81
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="language-c const-code" style="display:none;">
#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

const double Gravity = 9.81;

int main() {
    printf("%f\n", Gravity);
    return 0;
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Key Points</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Static:</strong> Belongs to the class, shared by all objects.</li>
        <li><strong>Readonly:</strong> Set once per object, either at declaration or in constructor.</li>
        <li><strong>Const:</strong> A compile-time constant, must be declared with a value.</li>
        <li>Use <strong>static</strong> for shared values, <strong>readonly</strong> for values set once per object, and <strong>const</strong> for fixed constants.</li>
    </ul>

